<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-227-208  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 227 208.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  May 1989 v10 n5 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Developments in digital radiography.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cannavo, Michael J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Filmless radiography is more expensive than traditional methods.andO;Stimulable plate technology has two problems: a throughput of 60plates per hour that necessitates the operation of two or moreprocessors in a typical radiology department, and a cost that maynecessitate justification of a million dollar expenditure for acomplete system.andP;  New technologies such as slot and fan beamscanning, digital image intensifier systems, and solid statesensors could replace film-screen combinations.andP;  Sensors are beingdeveloped with line pair resolution more than 20 lp-mm.andP;  Althoughsensors are far from being ready for medical use, they canpotentially produce approximately 2,000 exposures at $l-$2 per 14x 17 inch cassette.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RadiologyX-RaysHigh TechnologyMedical DiagnosisImage ProcessingSensorsResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>